revision.text:
{{Infobox knot theory | name= (−2,3,7) pretzel knot | practical name= | image= Pretzel knot.svg | caption= | arf invariant= 0 | bridge number= | crosscap number= 2 | crossing number= 12 | hyperbolic volume= 2.828122088 | linking number= | stick number= | unknotting number= 5 | conway_notation= [7;-2 1;2] | dowker notation= 4, 8, -16, 2, -18, -20, -22, -24, -6, -10, -12, -14 | d-t name= 12n242 | last crossing= 12n241 | last order= &nbsp; | next crossing= 12n243 | next order= &nbsp; | alternating= | class= hyperbolic | fibered= fibered | pretzel= pretzel | slice= | symmetry= reversible | tricolorable= }} In [[geometric topology]], a branch of [[mathematics]], the '''(&minus;2,&nbsp;3,&nbsp;7) pretzel knot''', sometimes called the '''Fintushel–Stern knot''' (after [[Ron Fintushel]] and [[Ronald J. Stern]]), is an important example of a [[pretzel link|pretzel knot]] which exhibits various interesting phenomena under three-dimensional and four-dimensional [[Surgery theory|surgery]] constructions.
== Mathematical properties ==
The (&minus;2,&nbsp;3,&nbsp;7) pretzel knot has 7 ''exceptional'' slopes, [[Dehn surgery]] slopes which give non-[[hyperbolic 3-manifold]]s. Among the enumerated knots, the only other hyperbolic knot with 7 or more is the [[figure-eight knot (mathematics)|figure-eight knot]], which has 10. All other hyperbolic knots are conjectured to have at most 6 exceptional slopes.
[[File:PretzelKnot.jpg|thumbnail|center|A pretzel (−2,3,7) pretzel knot.]]
