'''Luitpold''' (or '''Liutpold''') (modern ''Leopold'') (died 4 July 907), perhaps of the [[Huosi]] family or related to the [[Carolingian dynasty]] by Liutswind, mother of Emperor [[Arnulf of Carinthia]], was the ancestor of the [[Luitpoldings|Luitpolding dynasty]] which ruled [[History of Bavaria|Bavaria]] and [[Duchy of Carinthia|Carinthia]] until the mid-tenth century. 

In 893, he was appointed [[margrave]] in the [[March of Carinthia]] and Upper [[March of Pannonia|Pannonia]] by Arnulf of Carinthia, then King of [[East Francia]]. Luitpold succeeded the deposed Margrave [[Engelschalk II]] of the [[Wilhelminers|Wilhelminer]] family; unlike his predecessors he could extend his power unimpeded by the mighty Margrave [[Aribo of Austria|Aribo]], acquiring numerous counties in Carinthia as well as on the [[Danube]] and in the [[March of the Nordgau|Nordgau]] around [[Regensburg]] from 895 on, and setting himself up as the most prominent of Bavaria's aristocracy. Though he thereby laid the foundations of the renewed [[stem duchy]], it was his son [[Arnulf, Duke of Bavaria|Arnulf the Bad]] who, based on his father's acquisitions, first assumed the title of a [[List of rulers of Bavaria|Bavarian duke]].

As Luitpold remained a loyal supporter of the Carolingian monarch Arnulf of Carinthia and his son [[Louis the Child]], he enjoyed their support and was entrusted with the defence at the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] and [[Great Moravia|Moravia]]n borders. In 898 he fought successfully against [[Mojmír II]], the [[Great Moravia#List of rulers|king of Great Moravia]], on behalf of the king's rebellious brother [[Svatopluk II]] and forced Mojmír to become a vassal of Arnulf. In 903, Luitpold held the title of a ''dux Boemanorum'', "Duke in [[Bohemia]]". He organised the Frankish defence against the [[Hungarian people|Magyars]] under Grand Prince [[Árpád]] after invading Hungary, on 4 July 907 was killed east of Vienna in the [[Battle of Pressburg]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Barbarians, Marauders, and Infidels: The Ways of Medieval Warfare |last=Santosuosso |first=Antonio |authorlink=Antonio Santosuosso |year=2004 |publisher=MJF Books |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-56731-891-3|page=148 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>

==Marriage and issue==
Luitpold married [[Cunigunde of Swabia]],{{sfn|Muller-Mertens|1999|p=239}} daughter of Berthold I, royal [[Count palatine]] in [[Alamannia|Swabia]], and sister of Duke [[Erchanger, Duke of Swabia|Erchanger of Swabia]], a member of the [[Ahalolfings|Ahalolfing dynasty]]. After Luitpold's death Cunigunda married King [[Conrad I of Germany]] in 913.{{sfn|Muller-Mertens|1999|p=239}} Luitpold had two sons by her: 
*[[Arnulf, Duke of Bavaria|Arnulf the Bad]],{{sfn|Muller-Mertens|1999|p=239}} Duke of Bavaria from 907 to 937
*[[Berthold, Duke of Bavaria|Berthold]], Duke of Bavaria from 938 to 948.
From his descendants' titles, Luitpold is often called a duke of Bavaria or margrave of Bavaria, the latter title being more accurate to his actual status.

