[[File:Peter Allen MHA.jpg|thumb|right]]

'''Peter Allen''' (c. 1855 &ndash; 22 October 1925) was an Australian politician. He was a farmer and a correspondent for the ''[[Adelaide Advertiser]]'' before entering politics. He was a member of the [[South Australian House of Assembly]], representing [[Electoral district of Wallaroo|Wallaroo]] from 1902 to 1912 and [[Electoral district of Yorke Peninsula|Yorke Peninsula]] from 1915 to 1925 as a representative of the [[Farmers and Producers Political Union]], the [[Liberal Union (South Australia)|Liberal Union]] and [[Liberal Federation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Peter Allen|publisher=[[Parliament of South Australia]]|year=2011|url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Pages/default.aspx|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> He contested the [[Wallaroo by-election, 1891|1891 Wallaroo by-election]].

Prior to entering state politics, he was chairman of the [[District Council of Green's Plains]], and was the first chairman of the [[District Council of Kadina]] from 1888 to 1891.<ref name="stnaming">{{cite web | url=http://www.coppercoast.sa.gov.au/webdata/resources/files/Street_Naming_Policy1.pdf | title=10.1 ADOPTION OF COUNCIL POLICY – NAMING OF PUBLIC STREETS, ROADS, ETC | publisher=District Council of the Copper Coast | accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224355966 |title=Complimentary Social to Mr Peter Allen. |newspaper=[[Eyre's Peninsula Tribune]] |volume=II, |issue=62 |location=South Australia |date=10 May 1912 |accessdate=20 November 2016 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

